vectorData.altText: That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That's right! ’A’ is the popliteal artery. It is the continuation of the femoral artery. As femoral artery passes through the adductor hiatus, its name changes.

Turn your attention to the popliteal fossa, a diamond-shaped region in the posterior aspect of the knee.  Adipose tissue normally packs the popliteal fossa, and popliteal lymph nodes, deep lymph nodes of the leg, are located here. These tissues have been removed from the prosection in order to make the vessels easier for you to find.
IDENTIFY the popliteal artery and vein
Follow these vessels proximally, and observe that they enter the popliteal fossa by passing through a large gap in the insertion of the adductor magnus called the
relating to the knee; genu = knee

adductor hiatus. The popliteal artery and vein are the continuation of the femoral artery and vein; the name change occurs as they pass through the adductor hiatus. 
The genicular     anastomosis is a rich anastomosis that surrounds the knee. It consists of descending and ascending genicular arteries which anastomose freely around the joint. It can provide a clinically significant alternative route for blood to travel distally when an obstruction blocks the main arterial path through the popliteal artery.
